  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For this reason the Lord had driven out great and strong nations before the Israelites, so that no one was able to stand before them. The first hemistich points to the fulfilment of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 11:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the second to that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 11:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ואתּם is placed at the beginning absolutely. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the blessing of fidelity to the law which Israel had hitherto experienced, is described, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", upon the basis of the promise in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:7-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 28:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the thought of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is repeated. To this there is attached, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:11-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the admonition to take heed for the sake of their souls (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), to love the Lord their God (on the love of God as the sum of the fulfilment of the law, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 10:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 11:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). For if they turned, i.e., gave up the faithfulness they had hitherto displayed towards Jehovah, and attached themselves to the remnant of these nations, made marriages with them, and entered into fellowship with them, which the Lord had expressly forbidden (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:12-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), let them know that the Lord their God would not cut off these nations before them any more, but that they would be a snare and destruction to them. This threat is founded upon such passages of the law as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and more especially ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 33:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The figure of a trap, which is employed here (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 10:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is still further strengthened by פּח, a snare (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 8:14-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Shotet, a whip or scourge, an emphatic form of the word derived from the poel of שׁוּט, only occurs here. \"Scourges in your sides, and thorns in your eyes\" (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 33:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Joshua crowds his figures together to depict the misery and oppression which would be sure to result from fellowship with the Canaanites, because, from his knowledge of the fickleness of the people, and the wickedness of the human heart in its natural state, he could foresee that the apostasy of the nation from the Lord, which Moses had foretold, would take place but too quickly; as it actually did, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., in the very next generation. The words \"until ye perish,\" etc., resume the threat held out by Moses in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 11:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. Josh Deu 28:21.). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]